timeline.bodyText:
What about dropping the Characterinheritance ( and __typename and name fields here) to just keep:
interface Droid {
  val primaryFunction: String?
}

That would simplify the codegen a bunch. There's a minor annoyance that users won't be able to do hero.asDroid()?.name anymore but they can still achieve the same results with something like
when (hero) {
  is DroidHero -> // do something with hero.name and hero.primaryFunction
}

It might actually simplify the mental model since inline fragments would be closer to named fragments

replies.bodyText:
We can't do that as we merge parent fields from Character, so any fields that defined in parent field / fragment will be merged down to Droid interface. Otherwise we can easily run into clash of fields when build implementation for multiple fragments, like for instance:
interface Droid {
  friends: List<Friend>

  interface Friend {
    ...
  }
}

interface Character {
 friends: List<Friend>

  interface Friend {
    ...
  }
}

data class DroidCharacterHero(val friends: List<Friend>): Character, Droid


here we going to clash on friends as it ambiguous type

here we going to clash on friends as it ambiguous type

Since we're going to generate a data class for Friend, we could implement the different interfaces there?
interface Droid {
  friends: List<Friend>

  interface Friend {
    ...
  }
}

interface Character {
 friends: List<Friend>

  interface Friend {
    ...
  }
}

data class DroidCharacter(val friends: List<Friend>): Character, Droid {
  data class Friend([...]) : Character.Friend, Droid.Friend
}

This is more symmetrical.
